abstract: Gov Rod R Blagojevich says he will sign bill making Illinois first state to require police to record interrogations of homicide suspects; also supports many elements of second measure to overhaul death penalty system; photo (M)
snippet: Gov Rod R Blagojevich says he will sign bill making Illinois first state to require police to record interrogations of homicide suspects; also supports many elements of second measure to overhaul death penalty system; photo (M)
lead_paragraph: Though he once opposed the idea, Gov. Rod R. Blagojevich said he would sign a bill on Thursday that would make Illinois the first state to pass legislation requiring police to record their interrogations of homicide suspects.

abstract: Margaret Jean McFarland, the daughter of Mrs. J. Malcolm McFarland of Cranbury, N.J., and the late Mr. McFarland, was married yesterday to Dr. John Sante Symington, a son of Stuart Symington Jr., and Dr. Janey Symington of St. Louis. The Rev. Laurence D. Fish, an Episcopal priest, performed the ceremony in Hightstown, N.J., at the Ayer Memorial Chapel at the Peddie School, of which the bride is an alumna.

abstract: Amy Eileen Haidinger, daughter of Mr. and Mrs. Robert N. Haidinger of Riverside, Conn., was married there yesterday to Walter McNeill Rand, son of Mrs. Stanley Rand Jr. of Riverside and the late Mr. Rand.

abstract: Eddie Belmonte, one of the most successful riders of the late 1960's, was suspended yesterday as a jockey agent by the New York State Racing and Wagering Board in an outgrowth of the board's investigation into race-fixing.

abstract: In one important respect, European bridge organizers are ahead of their colleagues on this side of the Atlantic: They make considerable efforts to encourage young players to take up the game. In Sweden and the Netherlands, bridge is taught in schools with the aid of Government subsidies.
